14546-/// measures term-frequency, document-frequency, field length, and average field
14547-/// length under the index's own tokenization — porter stemming + unicode61
14548-/// case-fold + diacritic folding. The previous implementation hand-rolled a
14549-/// second lowercase-alnum splitter; a stemmed/diacritic variant recalled by
14550-/// `MATCH` (e.g. query `run` vs indexed `running`, or `cafe` vs `café`) was then
14551-/// scored as if the term were absent, so ranking was wrong for exactly those
14552-/// variants (codex §9 fix-1 finding 1). Reusing FTS5 itself makes scoring
14553-/// tokenization-faithful without re-implementing porter/unicode61 in Rust.
